Here is the solution in Julia:
```julia
function timezone_bumper(dt::DateTime, bump::Int=3)
    return dt + Hour(bump)
end

function timezone_bumper(dt::Date)
    error("This function works only for DateTime types and throws an error for Date types.")
end
```
In this code, the first function `timezone_bumper` accepts a DateTime type as its input along with an optional integer parameter `bump` that defaults to 3. It then returns a new DateTime object that is `bump` hours ahead of the original DateTime object. The second function `timezone_bumper` checks if the input is of Date type and throws an error if it is.
